talicized numerals and “1010” in black. She continues facing forward, eyebrows slightly raised, as if emphasizing how inexpensive it is. The middle-aged man in the blue shirt then appears beside the same “1010 987” logo, smiling knowingly toward the viewer.\n\nA mostly blank white screen follows, with “10 10” in black at the upper left. The logo builds again into “1010 987,” and a rate line appears beneath it: “3¢ a minute,” with the “3¢” in large red type and the rest in black.\n\nA young white woman with long, full, curly red hair appears centered against the white background. She wears a pink top or jacket with an open collar. She looks straight ahead, speaking with a bright, animated expression, then smiles. At the bottom, small white-on-shadow text reads “Available in most areas” on the left, and “Telecom USA” on the right. A blond white man appears next, wearing a dark short-sleeved shirt with white stripes on the sleeves. He stands casually, slightly angled, and smiles. The same bottom text remains: “Available in most areas” and “Telecom USA.”\n\nThe red-haired young woman returns in a tighter view, her face filling more of the screen. Her curly hair frames her face, and she looks directly ahead with wide eyes and a confident, pleased smile. The “Available in most areas” and “Telecom USA” notices remain along the bottom.\n\nAnother bold text question appears on the white background: “Could it be any easier?” The phrase builds in black and red, with “any” and “easier” in red and larger than the surrounding words.\n\nThe middle-aged man in the blue shirt reappears, now shown from about mid-thigh up. He stands with both hands on his hips, wearing jeans and a belt; a tan pouch or tool-like case hangs at his side. To his left, the dialing instructions appear visually. First “1010” appears in black, then the red “987” completes the logo. Beneath it, “+1” appears, followed by the words “and the number.” The layout visually demonstrates the calling sequence: dial “10